.\" DO NOT MODIFY THIS FILE!
.TH SENTINEL 1 "Mar 2026" "@sentinel_VERSION@" "sentinel manual"
.SH NAME
sentinel \- mutation testing tool for C/C++ projects
.SH SYNOPSIS
sentinel {OPTIONS}
.SH DESCRIPTION
sentinel runs a full mutation testing pipeline on a C/C++ project.
It seeds small, deliberate faults (mutants) into the source code, rebuilds the project,
runs the test suite, and reports which mutants were caught (killed) and which survived.
.PP
The mutation score — killed / (killed + survived) — measures how thoroughly the tests
cover the code under mutation.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Display the help menu.
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Print the program version and exit.
.SS Run options
.TP
\fB\-\-config\fR=\fIPATH\fR
Path to a YAML config file. When specified, sentinel changes to the
config file's directory before running, so all relative paths in the
config and build/test commands are resolved from that location.
When omitted, \fBsentinel.yaml\fR in the current directory is used
automatically if it exists.
.TP
\fB\-w\fR \fIPATH\fR, \fB\-\-workspace\fR=\fIPATH\fR
Directory for all run artifacts. Default: \fB./.sentinel\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-clean\fR
Clear the workspace and start a fresh run.
By default, sentinel automatically resumes an interrupted previous run.
Use \fB\-\-clean\fR to discard the previous state and start over.
.TP
\fB\-o\fR \fIPATH\fR, \fB\-\-output\-dir\fR=\fIPATH\fR
Directory to write HTML/XML reports.
.TP
\fB\-\-dry\-run\fR
Run only the build, test, and mutant-generation phases, then exit without
evaluating any mutants.
The workspace is preserved so that the next \fBsentinel\fR invocation (without \fB\-\-dry\-run\fR)
resumes directly at the evaluation phase, skipping build and generation.
.TP
\fB\-\-verbose\fR
Show build/test subprocess output on the terminal and enable verbose logging to stderr.
By default, subprocess output is suppressed (still written to workspace log files).
.TP
\fB\-\-no\-statusline\fR
Disable the live status line shown at the bottom of the terminal in TTY mode.
.SS Setup options
.TP
\fB\-\-init\fR
Write a \fBsentinel.yaml\fR config template to the current directory and exit.
Errors if the file already exists; use \fB\-\-force\fR to overwrite.
.TP
\fB\-\-force\fR
Overwrite existing files. Currently only affects \fB\-\-init\fR: allows overwriting
an existing \fBsentinel.yaml\fR without error.
.SS Build & test options
.TP
\fB\-\-source\-dir\fR=\fIPATH\fR
Root of the source tree to test. Default: \fB.\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-build\-command\fR=\fICMD\fR
Shell command to build the project. \fBRequired.\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-compiledb\-dir\fR=\fIPATH\fR
Directory containing \fBcompile_commands.json\fR.
Default: \fB.\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-test\-command\fR=\fICMD\fR
Shell command to run the test suite. \fBRequired.\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-test\-report\-dir\fR=\fIPATH\fR
Directory where the test command writes its result files. \fBRequired.\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-test\-report\-extension\fR=\fIEXT\fR
File extension of test result files (repeatable). Default: \fBxml\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-timeout\fR=\fISEC\fR
Test time limit in seconds. \fB0\fR = no limit.
Default: 2\(mu the measured baseline run time.
.TP
\fB\-\-kill\-after\fR=\fISEC\fR
Seconds to wait after \fB\-\-timeout\fR before sending SIGKILL to the test process.
\fB0\fR = disabled. Default: \fB60\fR
.SS Mutation options
.TP
\fB\-s\fR \fISCOPE\fR, \fB\-\-scope\fR=\fISCOPE\fR
Mutation scope: \fBcommit\fR limits mutation to lines changed in the latest git commit;
\fBall\fR mutates the entire codebase. Default: \fBall\fR
.TP
\fB\-t\fR \fIEXT\fR, \fB\-\-extension\fR=\fIEXT\fR
Source file extension to mutate (repeatable).
Default: \fBcxx cpp cc c c++ cu\fR
.TP
\fB\-p\fR \fIPATTERN\fR, \fB\-\-pattern\fR=\fIPATTERN\fR
Glob pattern to constrain the mutation scope (repeatable). Matched against
repository-relative paths. Prefix with \fB!\fR to exclude matching files
(e.g., \fB\-\-pattern="!*/test/*"\fR).
.TP
\fB\-l\fR \fIN\fR, \fB\-\-limit\fR=\fIN\fR
Maximum number of mutants to generate. \fB0\fR = evaluate all candidates. Default: \fB0\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-generator\fR=\fITYPE\fR
Mutant selection strategy: \fBuniform\fR, \fBrandom\fR, or \fBweighted\fR. Default: \fBuniform\fR
.TP
\fB\-\-seed\fR=\fIN\fR
Random seed for mutant selection. Default: random.
.TP
\fB\-\-operator\fR=\fIOP\fR
Mutation operator to apply (repeatable). Valid values:
\fBAOR\fR, \fBBOR\fR, \fBLCR\fR, \fBROR\fR, \fBSDL\fR, \fBSOR\fR, \fBUOI\fR.
Defaults to all operators when omitted.
.SS Advanced options
.TP
\fB\-\-coverage\fR=\fIFILE\fR
lcov coverage info file (repeatable). When given, only source lines covered by
tests are considered for mutation.
.TP
\fB\-\-partition\fR=\fIN\fR/\fITOTAL\fR
Evaluate only the N-th contiguous slice of the full mutant list out of TOTAL
partitions (1-based, e.g., \fB\-\-partition=2/5\fR).
It is recommended to set \fB\-\-seed\fR explicitly so that every partition instance
generates an identical mutant list; if omitted, a random seed is used and each
run may evaluate a different subset.
The union of all partition results is equivalent to a single non-partitioned run.
Mutant paths are stored relative to \fB\-\-source\-dir\fR, so workspace directories
can be collected from multiple machines and resumed on any machine with the same
source tree.
\fBNote:\fR source isolation and workspace separation between partition instances are the
responsibility of the calling environment.
.TP
\fB\-\-threshold\fR=\fIPCT\fR
Fail with exit code 3 if the mutation score is strictly below this percentage (0.0\(en100.0).
A one-line score summary is always written to stderr at the end of the run.
If no evaluable mutants exist, the threshold is not applied.
.SH COVERAGE-GUIDED MUTATION
The \fB\-\-coverage\fR option accepts an lcov coverage info file and restricts mutation
to source lines that are actually executed by the test suite.
This reduces the number of mutants and focuses testing on covered code.
The option can be repeated to merge multiple coverage files.
.PP
After running the tests with coverage instrumentation enabled, generate the coverage info
file with lcov:
.PP
.nf
lcov --capture --directory . --output-file coverage.info

# (Optional) Remove system and third-party paths
lcov --remove coverage.info '/usr/*' '*/third_party/*' --output-file coverage.info
.fi
.PP
Then pass it to sentinel via \fB\-\-coverage=coverage.info\fR.
.SH MUTATION OPERATORS
.TP
\fBAOR\fR \(em Arithmetic Operator Replacement
Replaces arithmetic operators: \fB+\fR \fB\-\fR \fB*\fR \fB/\fR \fB%\fR
.TP
\fBBOR\fR \(em Bitwise Operator Replacement
Replaces bitwise operators: \fB&\fR \fB|\fR \fB^\fR
.TP
\fBLCR\fR \(em Logical Connector Replacement
Replaces logical operators: \fB&&\fR \fB||\fR
.TP
\fBROR\fR \(em Relational Operator Replacement
Replaces relational operators: \fB<\fR \fB<=\fR \fB>\fR \fB>=\fR \fB==\fR \fB!=\fR
.TP
\fBSDL\fR \(em Statement Deletion
Deletes a statement body.
.TP
\fBSOR\fR \(em Shift Operator Replacement
Replaces shift operators: \fB<<\fR \fB>>\fR
.TP
\fBUOI\fR \(em Unary Operator Insertion
Inserts a unary operator before a variable reference.
.SH CONFIGURATION FILE
sentinel supports a YAML configuration file (\fBsentinel.yaml\fR) as an alternative
to passing all options on the command line.
When invoked, sentinel automatically looks for \fBsentinel.yaml\fR in the current
working directory. Use \fB\-\-config\fR to specify a different file.
.PP
All relative paths in \fBsentinel.yaml\fR are resolved relative to the file's own
location. sentinel also changes to that directory before executing build and test
commands, so paths in the config and shell commands share the same base.
.PP
CLI arguments always take priority over values in the configuration file:
.IP
CLI argument  >  sentinel.yaml  >  built-in default
.PP
Supported keys (all optional):
.TP
\fBsource-dir\fR
Root of the source tree to test.
.TP
\fBworkspace\fR
Directory for all run artifacts.
.TP
\fBoutput-dir\fR
Directory to write HTML/XML reports.
.TP
\fBcompiledb-dir\fR
Directory containing compile_commands.json.
.TP
\fBbuild-command\fR / \fBtest-command\fR
Shell commands to build the project and run the test suite.
.TP
\fBtest-result-dir\fR / \fBtest-result-ext\fR
Test result directory and file extensions.
.TP
\fBtimeout\fR / \fBkill-after\fR
Test time limit (seconds or \fBauto\fR) and post-timeout SIGKILL delay.
.TP
\fBscope\fR
Mutation scope: \fBcommit\fR or \fBall\fR.
.TP
\fBextension\fR
List of source file extensions to mutate.
.TP
\fBpattern\fR
List of paths/patterns to include or exclude (prefix with ! to exclude).
.TP
\fBgenerator\fR / \fBoperator\fR
Selection strategy and operator list.
.TP
\fBcoverage\fR
List of lcov coverage info files.
.SH EXAMPLES
Run mutation testing on a CMake project:
.PP
.nf
sentinel \\
  --source-dir=/path/to/project \\
  --build-command="cmake --build build" \\
  --test-command="ctest --test-dir build" \\
  --test-result-dir=build/test-results \\
  --scope=commit \\
  --limit=50
.fi
.PP
Generate a config file template:
.PP
.nf
sentinel --init
.fi
.SH UNDERSTANDING OUTPUT
sentinel produces output at three stages: generation, evaluation, and the final report.
.SS Mutant Population Report
After mutant generation, a summary table is printed showing the number of mutants
per file and per operator, the generator strategy, random seed, and how many
candidates were analyzed and selected.
The seed value can be reused with \fB\-\-seed\fR to reproduce the same mutant set.
.SS Per-Mutant Evaluation Results
During evaluation, each mutant result is printed as it completes.
Each line shows: a progress counter, a result icon
(\fB\[char"2717]\fR killed, \fB\[char"2713]\fR survived, \fB\[char"26A0]\fR skipped),
the mutation state, operator name, file:line, the original token, and build/test timing
in compact \fB[build/test]\fR format.
.PP
For killed mutants, the names of the killing tests are shown on the next line
(prefixed with \fB\[char"2190]\fR).
For build failures, timeouts, and runtime errors, the path to the relevant log file
is shown (prefixed with \fB\[char"21AA]\fR).
.SS Mutation Coverage Report
After all mutants are evaluated, sentinel prints a summary table to stdout showing
per-file and total statistics: \fBKilled\fR, \fBSurvived\fR, \fBTotal\fR, and \fBScore\fR.
Skipped mutants (build failures, timeouts, runtime errors) are listed separately.
A final one-line summary is also written to stderr.
.SS Mutation States
Each mutant evaluation results in one of five states:
.TP
\fBKilled\fR
A test failed on the mutant \(em the test suite detected the fault. This is the desired outcome.
.TP
\fBSurvived\fR
All tests passed despite the mutation \(em the fault went undetected.
This indicates a gap in test coverage.
.TP
\fBBuild Failure\fR
The mutant caused a compilation error. Excluded from the score.
.TP
\fBTimeout\fR
Tests exceeded the time limit. May indicate an infinite loop caused by the mutation.
Excluded from the score.
.TP
\fBRuntime Error\fR
Tests crashed or exited abnormally. Excluded from the score.
.SS Mutation Score
The mutation score is calculated as:
.IP
Score = Killed / (Killed + Survived) \(mu 100
.PP
Build failures, timeouts, and runtime errors are excluded and shown as "Skipped" in
the report. When no evaluable mutants exist, the score is displayed as \fB\-%\fR.
.SS Status Line
When stdout is a TTY, a live status line is displayed at the bottom of the terminal
throughout all phases. The symbols are:
\fB\[u2717]\fR = Killed, \fB\[u2713]\fR = Survived,
\fB\[u26A0]\fR = Abnormal (build failure, timeout, or runtime error).
Use \fB\-\-no\-statusline\fR to disable it.
.SH EXIT CODES
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
Runtime error (build failure, I/O error, invalid option value, etc.).
.TP
.B 2
CLI argument error (unknown option, missing required value, etc.).
.TP
.B 3
Mutation score is below the \fB\-\-threshold\fR value.
.SH REPORTING BUGS
sentinel issue tracker: <https://github.com/shift-left-test/sentinel/issues>
.SH SEE ALSO
sentinel repository: <https://github.com/shift-left-test/sentinel>,
Mutation Testing on Wikipedia: <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mutation_testing>
